content.description: Really fun route on loose and dirty rock.  This route is located to the right of the Goblet. Climb up a slab with one bolt, then immediately get into the business with funky sidepulls and loose blocky jugs.  Skip the nasty rusted 1/4" bolt up high.  Final mini crux before the lip.  Pull that and then slab climb up dirty and loose flakes to the anchors.
This is the bolt line to the right of steep street. It ascends a line of small and sloppy holds.
Start off on Nevergine and traverse right passed the first set of bolts and then up on the second.
content.location: This route has the same start at Neverigine and Powerless but strikes up the middle line of bolts.

content.description: An alternate start up some juggy holds to the right of the actual line. Two bolts gets you to the real route.
content.location: Next route to the right of Strip Clip. An alternative start.

content.description: This route climbs right along a juggy section to an angled corner, which leads to the slab above Nevermind's steepest section.
content.location: Begin left of the permadrawed overhang and climb up onto the slab above.

content.description: The second bolted route on the left of the wall.  Follows a series of fun jugs up a bulge to an anchor.  Well-protected fun climbing.  Might feel like an 11 at first, but once you know where the holds are, it gets a lot easier (like any route, I suppose).
This is the very first climb on the nevermind wall. It is tucked in the left corner.
content.protection: 4 bolts and chain anchor.  Shares an anchor with Steep Street.

content.description: Shared start with Neverigine, but move left and clip a high first bolt. Climb slightly overhanging jugs to a tricky crux, then finish at chains below a small tree.
content.location: Shared start with Neverigine, on the central juggy rail. Stick clip first bolt.

content.description: There's a crux right off the ground, and right below the chains.  Above the ledge keep to the left bolt line.
content.location: This route is just to the right of Negatherion.

content.description: The easiest route on the wall but also a bit contrived. Follow a right slanting line of bolts up the middle of Nevermind, following a jug rail for four bolts and then to a slight rest. Move up through a small crux, then traverse straight right for 5.9 or finish up two more bolts for the true .10a finish. Many other variations allow you to exit at different points for different grades.
The fourth route on the wall. Climb to a ledge and snag a rest and then power to the top.

Furthermost route on the right side of Nevermind Wall.  The start is slabby and is usually wet with muddy feet.  Head up and left into a dihedral, crank a few moves and pull over the lip to two chains.  No perma-draws at the top.  Good route but needs to climbed more to clean off some loose holds and dirt.
A tricky start leads to easier, fun climbing above
content.location: Shares the start win Easily Amused (5.10d), but breaks right

content.description: Go from left-end squeezy position to right. Do this when your harness is right at home.
Go from right-end nice jugs to left tricky shoulder move. Do this when your harness is left at home.
The third-to-last route on the wall. Arguably a bit tougher than Culture Shock. This route is thuggy on Nevermind's most overhaning section.
content.protection: 5 bolts and permadraw anchor. All bolts but the first have permadraws as well.

content.description: Climb the first four bolts of "The Goblet" and then cut left into the second crux of "Culture Shock".  Equally as fun as "Culture Shock" and feels less contrived than the finish of "The Goblet".

10 bolts 5.10c. Slopey face climbing leads to the first clip. A couple tricky boulder problems lead to lower angle terrain and link into the first pitch of the ascentionist. The crux is well protected with the easier terrain sporting a bit of space on the bolts. It was put up with the intent of being a direct first pitch variation to the ascentionist. It has some genuinely fun movement and will stay considerably drier than the standard first pitch. It would also be a fun standalone climb (although it will have distinctly bold feeling compared to your standard x38 affair) It cleaned up well but is quite dusty.
content.location: The route starts below an obvious roof about 40 ft to the left of the ascentionist corner.

content.description: Sustained, pumpy.  Solid holds
content.location: Middle section, same start as Love Bucket, follow the bolt line up and to the left

content.description: This is the second bolted line from the the right. It ascends the steepest section of Nevermind. After a few clips of thuggery the wall straightens a bit to a very cool crux sequence. Once that is figured out it's just simple cranking to the top.
content.protection: 9 bolts, chain anchor. Permadraw on 4th bolt.

content.description: Climb the black streak following the right line of bolts above the ledge.
Start on "Easily Amused", then trend left into "Hangerville".  Follow the right line of bolts to the topmost set of chains, the anchor for "Hangerville".
middle bulge crux, and super pumpy at top out.One of the not over-rated climbs at X38.which is 11b, and should stay that way.
content.location: left of Big Mamma, right of Architect Rally

content.description: Start on Canine Patrol. At the crux bulge of Canine (about the 7th bolt) traverse left to finish on the last three bolts of Architect Rally. The traverse sequence adds an interesting new dimension to this climb, and probably adds a letter grade of difficulty to Architect, but feels easier than the crux of Canine.
content.location: Starts on the first bolt line left of Strip Clip (the obvious right-leaning ramp), then finishes at the anchors of the bolt line that starts ~15 ft left of this start.

content.description:
Large polished hold separated by big, thugish moves--A good route for the gym rat!

Start up the moderalte ramp on the right side of the crag.  After five bolts, step out to the left and tackle the steep headwall above you.

Don't let the pump beat you to the anchors!
content.protection: 9 bolts, plus an additional 2 for the chain anchors.
content.location: On the right side of the crag above the obvious ramplike feature.

content.description:
I believe this project started one desperate rainy day March 2017. Too wet to do ANYTHING, but the stoke was high. Kyle touted "I want to do something stupid." I had it in the back of my mind that this wall existed, but never had a reason to explore. We went out armed for bear, full double rack, aid kit and a hammer drill. We were going to siege our way up the wall in the rain. A couple hours later and out of rivets the first pitch was done... Over the course of the summer we would go out and chip away at a pitch, limited by the battery life of the drill (hand drilling in this rock was crazy, way more effort than granite it seemed). Most of the rack was left on the ground after pitch 2. I daisy whipped on a #2 and had it pull, tomahawking backwards through the moss for 40 ft. With full aid kit and the drill in hand it was an entertaining fall. We eventually made it up the wall 5.9 A2+ R. (Side note: if some of the bolting seems weird, many bolts were placed on aid lead through a blanket of gravel and moss so...) So then commenced the absurd task of cleaning this wall. Hundreds of hours went into cleaning it to the state that its in. We had caution tape up for quite a while and gated off nevermind on days we were planning to release big stuff. Most of the climbing is surprisingly fun, some being legitimately wild. Be prepared for some post cleaning dirt and the potential for holds to pull. Overall the route cleaned up fairly well, but until this thing sees a lot of ascents rockfall may still be commonplace. Bring a hardhat!

P1 (5.8/9, 120ft, 13 bolts) - Climb up the left facing corner to the massive roof, traverse left past the roof then up the face to a sloping ledge with chains.

P2 (5.10b, 110ft, 14 bolts) - Boulder problem to the right of the belay takes you up the groove, then climb slab up to a broken face. Climb easy moves to a big ledge with rap chains, step right stem off tree, then steep moves up (crux) then lead you left past some more broken rock. Belay at a stance, 2 bolts w/no chain.

P3 (5.10b, 100ft, 13 bolts) - The money pitch. Traverse right from the belay to some yellow rock, mantle to a sloping ledge, then do some wild moves to initiate a traverse back left to a big ledge with a belay.

P4 (5.8/9, 60ft, 6 bolts) - Climb straight up the face to a ledge with a tree, 3 bolt anchor (1 damaged, 1 wire hanger, 1 good).

P5 (5.9+, 130ft, 12 bolts) - Climb up the easy face to a slab with an (easy) runout to a ledge. Optional belay here to do 4,5,6 as 2 pitches. Pull some steep moves off the ledge and traverse a massive dike right to a huge ledge with an anchor. (Do not rap here, else you want to adventure through choss land!)

P6 (5.9, 60ft, 5 bolts) - Steep moves off the belay, then climb up and left to the top.

Descent - 5 single rope raps straight down the route.
content.protection: 15 quickdraws, or 30 if simulclimbing. Of these you'll want about 4 (or 8ish) alpine draws. 60m rope. Helmets.
content.location: Approach to Nevermind, then continue to the right past the crag a couple hundred yards. The route starts in the large, obvious left facing corner.

content.description:
A fun, well-protected, and sequency route that challenges the climber to rely heavily on good footwork, stamina, and route finding skills.

This route begins below the inobvious, blocky, left-facing corner two routes to the left of the obvious 5.9 ramp on the right side of the crag.  Climb some moderately technical terrain to a definite crux  that guards the bottomless dihedral below the anchor.
content.location: The right side of the cliff, two routes to the left of the 5.9 ramp below a shallow left-facing, blocky corner.
